    class MyArrayObject {
        private String name;
        private String course;
        private long id;
        
        public MyArrayObject(String name, String course, long id) {
            this.name = name;
            this.course = course;
            this.id = id;
        }
    }


...and then fill you array like that

    students[0] = new MyArrayObject(&quot;John Doe&quot;, &quot;2BA&quot;, 444444);
    students[1] = new MyArrayObject(&quot;Jane Doe&quot;, &quot;2BA&quot;, 445566);
    students[2] = new MyArrayObject(&quot;John Smith&quot;, &quot;2BSc&quot;, 442200);


It&#39;s still spaghetti code, but less.

To give you a better answer, we need more information about the object, where it comes from, what data sources you have, why you use such hardcoded values anyway.

You can use a file that contains your data. You may chose any format (XML, json, CSV, etc).
Lets say you chose CSV which is one of the simplest formats to represent your data.
Each line on your CSV would contain:

Name, Course, ID

Write some code to read the file line by line into a String. Then for each line (each String) you can do:

    String [] studentsStr = line.split(&#39;,&#39;);

Then your array will hold 3 Strings at indexes: 

1: Name  2: Course  3: ID

As your CSV file could contain a non-deterministic size of students, you can use an ArraList.

Declare the array list

    List&lt;Student&gt; studentL = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

For each line on the CSV text file:

    Student std = new Student();
    std.setName(studentsStr[0]);
    std.setCourse(studentsStr[1]);
    std.setID(studentsStr[2]);
    studentL.add(std);

Then you can add as many students as you want into your CSV without any changes in your code.

